window.PROBLEMS = {"sections": [{"id": "getting-started", "title": "Getting Started", "problems": [{"id": "greet-by-name", "title": "Greet by Name", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Print a friendly greeting for a given name.\n\nGiven a name stored in the variable `name`, print `Hello, <name>!` on its own line.\n\n### Example\n```python\nname = \"Ada\"\n# expected output:\nHello, Ada!\n```", "hints": ["An f-string lets you drop a variable straight into text: `f\"...\"`.", "Inside an f-string, wrap the variable in curly braces: `f\"Hello, {name}\"`.", "The exclamation mark goes *inside* the quotes, right after the closing brace."], "solutions": [{"label": "f-string", "code": "name = \"Ada\"\nprint(f\"Hello, {name}!\")", "explanation": "An f-string (the `f` before the quotes) substitutes anything inside `{}` with its value."}, {"label": "Joining with +", "code": "name = \"Ada\"\nprint(\"Hello, \" + name + \"!\")", "explanation": "You can also build the string by joining pieces with `+`. Every piece has to be a string."}]}, {"id": "add-two-numbers", "title": "Add Two Numbers", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Given two numbers `a` and `b`, print their sum.\n\n### Example\n```python\na = 7\nb = 5\n# expected output:\n12\n```", "hints": ["The `+` operator adds two numbers together.", "Store the result in a variable, then `print` that variable.", "`print(a + b)` works directly too — no temporary variable needed."], "solutions": [{"label": "Solution", "code": "a = 7\nb = 5\ntotal = a + b\nprint(total)", "explanation": "Add the two values, keep the result in `total`, then print it."}]}, {"id": "even-or-odd", "title": "Even or Odd", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Given a whole number `n`, print `even` if it is even and `odd` if it is odd.\n\n### Example\n```python\nn = 10   ->  even\nn = 7    ->  odd\n```\n\n### Hint to think about\nA number is even when dividing it by 2 leaves **no remainder**.", "hints": ["The remainder operator `%` gives what's left after division: `10 % 2` is `0`.", "If `n % 2 == 0`, the number is even; otherwise it's odd.", "Use an `if` / `else` block to print the right word."], "solutions": [{"label": "if / else", "code": "n = 10\nif n % 2 == 0:\n    print(\"even\")\nelse:\n    print(\"odd\")", "explanation": "`%` is the modulo operator. An even number divided by 2 has remainder 0."}, {"label": "One-liner", "code": "n = 10\nprint(\"even\" if n % 2 == 0 else \"odd\")", "explanation": "A conditional expression (`A if condition else B`) chooses a value inline."}]}, {"id": "price-with-tax", "title": "Price With Tax", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "A product costs `price` dollars before tax. Tax is **10%**. Print the final price including tax.\n\n```python\nprice = 120\n# 120 + 10% of 120  =  120 + 12  ->  132.0\n```", "hints": ["10% of a number is `number * 0.10`. The final price is the original plus that tax.", "You can do it in one step: multiplying by `1.10` adds 10% on top of the original.", "`print(price * 1.10)` — multiplying a whole number by a decimal gives a decimal result, `132.0`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Add the tax", "code": "price = 120\ntax = price * 0.10\nprint(price + tax)", "explanation": "Work out the tax, then add it back on."}, {"label": "Multiply by 1.1", "code": "price = 120\nprint(price * 1.10)", "explanation": "Multiplying by `1.10` is the same as adding 10% in a single step."}]}, {"id": "celsius-to-fahrenheit", "title": "Celsius to Fahrenheit", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Convert a temperature in Celsius to Fahrenheit. The formula is `F = C * 9 / 5 + 32`.\n\n```python\nc = 25\n# 25 * 9 / 5 + 32  =  45 + 32  ->  77.0\n```", "hints": ["Translate the formula straight into Python: multiply and divide first, then add 32.", "`c * 9 / 5` does the scaling; Python runs `*` and `/` left to right before the `+ 32`.", "`print(c * 9 / 5 + 32)`. Because `/` always produces a float, the answer prints as `77.0`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Apply the formula", "code": "c = 25\nf = c * 9 / 5 + 32\nprint(f)", "explanation": "Type the maths formula directly; `/` makes the result a float."}]}, {"id": "percent-complete", "title": "Percent Complete", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "You've finished `done` tasks out of `total`. Print what **percent** is complete, rounded to one decimal place.\n\n```python\ndone = 18\ntotal = 24\n# 18 / 24 = 0.75  ->  75.0\n```", "hints": ["A percent is a fraction times 100: `done / total * 100`.", "Compute the fraction first; `done / total * 100` runs left to right, so it works out correctly.", "Wrap it for one decimal place: `round(done / total * 100, 1)`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Fraction times 100", "code": "done = 18\ntotal = 24\nprint(round(done / total * 100, 1))", "explanation": "Divide to get the fraction, scale by 100, round to one place."}]}, {"id": "in-stock", "title": "In Stock?", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "A warehouse has `units` of an item on hand. Print `\"in stock\"` if there is at least one unit, otherwise `\"out of stock\"`.\n\n```python\nunits = 0   ->  out of stock\nunits = 7   ->  in stock\n```", "hints": ["This is a yes/no decision — an `if` / `else` chooses between the two messages.", "'At least one' means `units >= 1` (the same as `units > 0`).", "`if units >= 1: print(\"in stock\")`, with an `else:` branch for the other message."], "solutions": [{"label": "if / else", "code": "units = 7\nif units >= 1:\n    print(\"in stock\")\nelse:\n    print(\"out of stock\")", "explanation": "The condition picks which of the two messages to print."}]}, {"id": "longer-word", "title": "Longer Word", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Given two words `a` and `b`, print whichever is **longer** (more letters). On a tie, print `a`.\n\n```python\na = \"truck\"\nb = \"van\"\n# 'truck' has 5 letters, 'van' has 3  ->  truck\n```", "hints": ["`len(a)` is the number of letters in `a`. Compare the two lengths.", "If `len(a) >= len(b)`, `a` wins — the `>=` sends ties to `a`.", "`print(a if len(a) >= len(b) else b)` chooses inline, or use a full `if` / `else`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Compare lengths", "code": "a = \"truck\"\nb = \"van\"\nif len(a) >= len(b):\n    print(a)\nelse:\n    print(b)", "explanation": "Compare the lengths and print the word attached to the bigger one."}, {"label": "One-liner", "code": "a = \"truck\"\nb = \"van\"\nprint(a if len(a) >= len(b) else b)", "explanation": "A conditional expression picks the word to print in a single line."}]}, {"id": "absolute-difference", "title": "Forecast Error", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "A forecast predicted `forecast` orders; `actual` came in. Print the **size of the error** — how far off the forecast was, as a positive number.\n\n```python\nforecast = 120\nactual = 95\n# off by |120 - 95|  ->  25\n```", "hints": ["The error could land above or below the forecast; you want its *size*, so use `abs(...)`.", "`abs(forecast - actual)` is the distance between the two, never negative.", "`print(abs(forecast - actual))` — both `abs(-25)` and `abs(25)` give `25`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Absolute value", "code": "forecast = 120\nactual = 95\nprint(abs(forecast - actual))", "explanation": "`abs()` strips the sign, leaving just how far apart the numbers are."}]}, {"id": "initials", "title": "Initials", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Given a full name, print the person's **initials** in uppercase, joined by a dot.\n\n```python\nname = \"ada lovelace\"  ->  A.L\nname = \"grace hopper\"  ->  G.H\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThree small moves: split the name into words, grab the first letter of each, and join those letters with a dot.", "hints": ["`name.split()` breaks the full name into a list of words at the spaces.", "For each word you want its first letter — `word[0]` — uppercased with `.upper()`.", "Collect the letters, then `\".\".join(initials)` glues them with dots between."], "solutions": [{"label": "Split and take firsts", "code": "name = \"ada lovelace\"\ninitials = []\nfor word in name.split():\n    initials.append(word[0].upper())\nprint(\".\".join(initials))", "explanation": "One first-letter per word, collected into a list, then joined with dots."}, {"label": "Comprehension", "code": "name = \"ada lovelace\"\nprint(\".\".join(w[0].upper() for w in name.split()))", "explanation": "The same steps compressed into one line once the pattern is familiar."}]}]}, {"id": "loops-and-logic", "title": "Loops & Logic", "problems": [{"id": "fizzbuzz", "title": "FizzBuzz", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Print the numbers from 1 to `n`, one per line, with two twists:\n\n- For multiples of **3**, print `Fizz` instead of the number.\n- For multiples of **5**, print `Buzz` instead of the number.\n- For multiples of **both 3 and 5**, print `FizzBuzz`.\n\n### Example (n = 5)\n```\n1\n2\nFizz\n4\nBuzz\n```", "hints": ["Loop over the numbers with `for i in range(1, n + 1):` — `range` stops *before* the second value.", "Check the both-case first: `if i % 3 == 0 and i % 5 == 0:` before checking 3 or 5 alone.", "Order matters — if you check `% 3` first, 15 would print `Fizz` and never reach the combined case."], "solutions": [{"label": "Classic", "code": "n = 15\nfor i in range(1, n + 1):\n    if i % 3 == 0 and i % 5 == 0:\n        print(\"FizzBuzz\")\n    elif i % 3 == 0:\n        print(\"Fizz\")\n    elif i % 5 == 0:\n        print(\"Buzz\")\n    else:\n        print(i)", "explanation": "Check the combined 3-and-5 case first, then the single cases, then fall back to the number."}, {"label": "Build a word", "code": "n = 15\nfor i in range(1, n + 1):\n    word = \"\"\n    if i % 3 == 0:\n        word += \"Fizz\"\n    if i % 5 == 0:\n        word += \"Buzz\"\n    print(word or i)", "explanation": "Build up the word in pieces; `word or i` prints the number when `word` is still empty."}]}, {"id": "sum-from-1-to-n", "title": "Sum from 1 to N", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Given a number `n`, print the sum of every whole number from 1 up to and including `n`.\n\n### Example\n```python\nn = 5   ->  15      # because 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5\n```", "hints": ["Keep a running `total` that starts at 0, and add each number to it in a loop.", "`for i in range(1, n + 1):` walks through 1, 2, ... up to n.", "Python's built-in `sum()` can add up a whole range at once."], "solutions": [{"label": "Loop", "code": "n = 5\ntotal = 0\nfor i in range(1, n + 1):\n    total += i\nprint(total)", "explanation": "`total += i` is shorthand for `total = total + i`, applied once per number."}, {"label": "Built-in sum", "code": "n = 5\nprint(sum(range(1, n + 1)))", "explanation": "`sum()` adds every value produced by the range — no manual loop needed."}]}, {"id": "count-the-vowels", "title": "Count the Vowels", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Given a lowercase word stored in `word`, print how many vowels (`a e i o u`) it contains.\n\n### Example\n```python\nword = \"python\"  ->  1\nword = \"banana\"  ->  3\n```", "hints": ["You can loop over a string letter by letter: `for letter in word:`.", "Keep a `count` variable and add 1 whenever the letter is a vowel.", "Check membership with `in`: `if letter in \"aeiou\":`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Loop and count", "code": "word = \"banana\"\ncount = 0\nfor letter in word:\n    if letter in \"aeiou\":\n        count += 1\nprint(count)", "explanation": "`letter in \"aeiou\"` is True when the letter is one of those five characters."}, {"label": "Sum a comprehension", "code": "word = \"banana\"\nprint(sum(1 for letter in word if letter in \"aeiou\"))", "explanation": "The generator yields a 1 for each vowel; `sum` adds them up. A compact pattern once you're comfortable with loops."}]}, {"id": "countdown", "title": "Countdown", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Print a countdown from `n` down to 1, one number per line.\n\n```python\nn = 5\n# expected output:\n5\n4\n3\n2\n1\n```", "hints": ["`range` can step backwards when you give it a negative step.", "`range(n, 0, -1)` yields n, n-1, ... down to 1 (it stops *before* 0).", "`for i in range(n, 0, -1): print(i)` prints one number per turn."], "solutions": [{"label": "Range with a negative step", "code": "n = 5\nfor i in range(n, 0, -1):\n    print(i)", "explanation": "A step of -1 walks the range downward, stopping just before 0."}]}, {"id": "multiplication-table", "title": "Multiplication Table", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Print the times table for `n`, from `n x 1` up to `n x 10`.\n\n```python\nn = 3\n# expected output:\n3 x 1 = 3\n3 x 2 = 6\n...\n3 x 10 = 30\n```", "hints": ["Loop the multiplier from 1 to 10: `for k in range(1, 11):` (range stops before 11).", "Each line needs three values — `n`, `k`, and the product `n * k`.", "An f-string lays it out: `print(f\"{n} x {k} = {n * k}\")`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Loop and format", "code": "n = 3\nfor k in range(1, 11):\n    print(f\"{n} x {k} = {n * k}\")", "explanation": "One line per multiplier, built with an f-string that drops in the product."}]}, {"id": "factorial", "title": "Factorial", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Print `n` factorial — the product `1 * 2 * 3 * ... * n`.\n\n```python\nn = 5\n# 1 * 2 * 3 * 4 * 5  ->  120\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is a **running product** — the cousin of a running total. The catch: what must the accumulator start at, so the very first multiply doesn't wipe it out?", "hints": ["Running-product pattern: keep a `result` and multiply each number in. Start it at **1**, not 0 — starting at 0 makes everything 0.", "Loop the numbers to multiply in: `for i in range(1, n + 1):`.", "Inside: `result *= i` (short for `result = result * i`). Print after the loop."], "solutions": [{"label": "Running product", "code": "n = 5\nresult = 1\nfor i in range(1, n + 1):\n    result *= i\nprint(result)", "explanation": "Like a running total, but multiplying — so it starts at 1 instead of 0."}]}, {"id": "count-multiples-of-3", "title": "Count Multiples of 3", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Print how many numbers from 1 to `n` are **multiples of 3**.\n\n```python\nn = 20\n# 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18  ->  6\n```", "hints": ["Conditional counter: `count = 0` before the loop, add 1 whenever the test passes.", "A number is a multiple of 3 when it divides evenly: `i % 3 == 0`.", "Loop `for i in range(1, n + 1):` and `count += 1` inside `if i % 3 == 0:`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Count with modulo", "code": "n = 20\ncount = 0\nfor i in range(1, n + 1):\n    if i % 3 == 0:\n        count += 1\nprint(count)", "explanation": "Walk every number and tick the counter on each multiple of 3."}, {"label": "Math shortcut", "code": "n = 20\nprint(n // 3)", "explanation": "Whole-number division by 3 counts the multiples of 3 up to n directly."}]}, {"id": "triangle-of-stars", "title": "Triangle of Stars", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Print a left-aligned triangle of `*`, `n` rows tall: row 1 has one star, row 2 has two, and so on.\n\n```python\nn = 4\n# expected output:\n*\n**\n***\n****\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nEach row is a string of stars whose length is the row number. You can **build** that string directly instead of looping a second time.", "hints": ["Loop the row numbers 1..n: `for row in range(1, n + 1):`.", "Python repeats a string with `*`: `\"*\" * 3` is `\"***\"`. The count is the row number.", "`print(\"*\" * row)` once per row draws the growing triangle."], "solutions": [{"label": "Repeat the star", "code": "n = 4\nfor row in range(1, n + 1):\n    print(\"*\" * row)", "explanation": "`\"*\" * row` makes a row of exactly the right length."}, {"label": "Nested loop", "code": "n = 4\nfor row in range(1, n + 1):\n    line = \"\"\n    for _ in range(row):\n        line += \"*\"\n    print(line)", "explanation": "The inner loop builds each row one star at a time — the long-hand version."}]}, {"id": "largest-digit", "title": "Largest Digit", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Given a positive whole number `n`, print its **largest digit**.\n\n```python\nn = 49072\n# digits 4, 9, 0, 7, 2  ->  9\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nA number isn't directly loopable, but its **text** is. Turn it into a string and you can walk it digit by digit, tracking the biggest.", "hints": ["Turn the number into something you can loop over: `for ch in str(n):` gives one digit-character at a time.", "Find-the-extreme pattern: keep `biggest = 0` and update it whenever a larger digit appears.", "Compare as numbers: `digit = int(ch)`, then `if digit > biggest: biggest = digit`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Scan the digits", "code": "n = 49072\nbiggest = 0\nfor ch in str(n):\n    digit = int(ch)\n    if digit > biggest:\n        biggest = digit\nprint(biggest)", "explanation": "Looping the string form lets you inspect each digit and keep the largest."}, {"label": "Built-in max", "code": "n = 49072\nprint(max(int(ch) for ch in str(n)))", "explanation": "`max` runs the same find-the-extreme scan over the digits for you."}]}, {"id": "collatz-steps", "title": "Collatz Steps", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Start from a number `n`. Each step: if it is **even**, halve it; if it is **odd**, do `3 * n + 1`. Count how many steps it takes to reach **1**.\n\n```python\nn = 6\n# 6 -> 3 -> 10 -> 5 -> 16 -> 8 -> 4 -> 2 -> 1  ->  8 steps\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nYou don't know the step count ahead of time, so reach for `while`: keep going *while* `n` isn't 1 yet, branching each step on even vs odd.", "hints": ["Loop until you arrive: `while n != 1:`. Count with `steps = 0`, adding 1 each pass.", "Branch on even/odd inside: `if n % 2 == 0:` do `n = n // 2`, `else:` do `n = 3 * n + 1`.", "Increment `steps += 1` once per pass (either branch). Print `steps` after the loop."], "solutions": [{"label": "while with a branch", "code": "n = 6\nsteps = 0\nwhile n != 1:\n    if n % 2 == 0:\n        n = n // 2\n    else:\n        n = 3 * n + 1\n    steps += 1\nprint(steps)", "explanation": "Each pass transforms `n` and counts a step until it lands on 1."}]}]}, {"id": "loops-over-data", "title": "Loops Over Data", "problems": [{"id": "total-package-weight", "title": "Total Package Weight", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "A delivery van is loaded with parcels. Each parcel's weight in kilograms is in the list `weights`. Print the **total** weight on the van.\n\n```python\nweights = [12, 5, 8, 20, 3]\n# expected output:\n48\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is the most common shape in data work: a **running total**. Before writing any loop, answer two questions — *what variable holds the total, and what does it start at?*", "hints": ["Running-total pattern: create `total = 0` **before** the loop, then add to it inside. The starting value matters — a sum starts at 0.", "Loop over the data itself, not a range of numbers: `for w in weights:` hands you each weight in turn as `w`.", "Inside the loop: `total += w`. Put `print(total)` **after** the loop (no indentation) so it runs once at the end, not once per parcel."], "solutions": [{"label": "Running total", "code": "weights = [12, 5, 8, 20, 3]\ntotal = 0\nfor w in weights:\n    total += w\nprint(total)", "explanation": "Start the accumulator at 0, add each weight as you pass it, print once at the end."}, {"label": "Built-in sum", "code": "weights = [12, 5, 8, 20, 3]\nprint(sum(weights))", "explanation": "`sum()` is the running-total loop wrapped up for you. Write it by hand first, then reach for `sum()`."}]}, {"id": "count-late-deliveries", "title": "Count the Late Deliveries", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "`days` holds how many days each order took to arrive. Anything over **3 days** counts as *late*. Print how many orders were late.\n\n```python\ndays = [2, 5, 1, 7, 3, 6]\n# the late ones are 5, 7, 6  ->  3\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is a **conditional counter**: walk every record, but bump the counter *only when a condition is true*.", "hints": ["Counter pattern: `late = 0` before the loop. You're counting events, so it starts at 0 just like a total.", "Inside the loop, test each value first: `if d > 3:` — only then is it late.", "`late += 1` goes inside the `if`. The amount you add is always 1 (you're counting orders, not adding up the days)."], "solutions": [{"label": "Count with a condition", "code": "days = [2, 5, 1, 7, 3, 6]\nlate = 0\nfor d in days:\n    if d > 3:\n        late += 1\nprint(late)", "explanation": "The `if` decides *whether* to count; `+= 1` does the counting."}, {"label": "Sum a condition", "code": "days = [2, 5, 1, 7, 3, 6]\nprint(sum(1 for d in days if d > 3))", "explanation": "Each matching order contributes a 1; `sum` totals them. The same count, written compactly."}]}, {"id": "average-delivery-time", "title": "Average Delivery Time", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Using the same delivery times, print the **average** number of days, rounded to one decimal place.\n\n```python\ndays = [2, 5, 1, 7, 3, 6]\n# (2 + 5 + 1 + 7 + 3 + 6) / 6  =  24 / 6  ->  4.0\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nAn average is two patterns stacked: a **total** and a **count**, divided at the very end. You already know both.", "hints": ["You need two numbers from one pass: the sum of the days, and how many there are. Keep `total = 0`; the count is just `len(days)`.", "Divide **after** the loop, never inside it — you can only average once you've seen every value.", "`round(total / len(days), 1)` gives one decimal place. (Heads-up: dividing by `len([])` crashes on an empty list — safe here since this list isn't empty.)"], "solutions": [{"label": "Sum then divide", "code": "days = [2, 5, 1, 7, 3, 6]\ntotal = 0\nfor d in days:\n    total += d\naverage = total / len(days)\nprint(round(average, 1))", "explanation": "Accumulate the total in the loop, then divide by how many there were."}, {"label": "Built-ins", "code": "days = [2, 5, 1, 7, 3, 6]\nprint(round(sum(days) / len(days), 1))", "explanation": "`sum` and `len` are the total and the count — the average is just one divided by the other."}]}, {"id": "filter-big-shipments", "title": "Filter the Big Shipments", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Build and print a **new list** containing only the shipments that weigh **15 kg or more** (those need a second handler).\n\n```python\nweights = [12, 5, 18, 20, 3, 16]\n# expected output:\n[18, 20, 16]\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is the **filter** shape: start with an empty list, then `append` only the items that pass a test. Counting and filtering are twins — one keeps a number, the other keeps the items themselves.", "hints": ["Filter pattern: make an empty `heavy = []` before the loop. You're collecting items, so it starts empty — not 0.", "Inside the loop, test then collect: `if w >= 15:` and only then `heavy.append(w)`.", "Keep `print(heavy)` outside the loop — you want the finished list once, not a print per item."], "solutions": [{"label": "Build a filtered list", "code": "weights = [12, 5, 18, 20, 3, 16]\nheavy = []\nfor w in weights:\n    if w >= 15:\n        heavy.append(w)\nprint(heavy)", "explanation": "Empty list + append-if-it-matches is the filter pattern you'll use constantly in data work."}, {"label": "List comprehension", "code": "weights = [12, 5, 18, 20, 3, 16]\nprint([w for w in weights if w >= 15])", "explanation": "A comprehension is the filter loop on one line: keep `w` for each `w` in `weights` that passes the test."}]}, {"id": "label-each-order", "title": "Label Each Order", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Build a new list that labels each order `\"on time\"` (3 days or fewer) or `\"late\"`, keeping the same order.\n\n```python\ndays = [2, 5, 1, 7]\n# expected output:\n['on time', 'late', 'on time', 'late']\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is the **transform** shape: one input item turns into one output item, so the new list ends up the *same length* as the old one. (Filtering changes the length; transforming never does.)", "hints": ["Transform pattern: empty `labels = []`, then `append` exactly once per order — every order produces one label.", "Decide the label first, then append it. A conditional expression helps: `\"late\" if d > 3 else \"on time\"`.", "Notice there's no `if` wrapped around the `append` here — unlike a filter, *every* item gets added. The `if` only chooses which label."], "solutions": [{"label": "Transform each item", "code": "days = [2, 5, 1, 7]\nlabels = []\nfor d in days:\n    if d > 3:\n        labels.append(\"late\")\n    else:\n        labels.append(\"on time\")\nprint(labels)", "explanation": "Every order maps to exactly one label, so the result is the same length as the input."}, {"label": "With a conditional expression", "code": "days = [2, 5, 1, 7]\nlabels = []\nfor d in days:\n    labels.append(\"late\" if d > 3 else \"on time\")\nprint(labels)", "explanation": "`\"late\" if d > 3 else \"on time\"` picks the value inline, so one `append` covers both cases."}]}, {"id": "heaviest-shipment", "title": "Find the Heaviest Shipment", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Two parallel lists describe today's parcels: `ids` and `weights` (same length, lined up by position). Print the **id of the heaviest** parcel.\n\n```python\nids     = [\"A1\", \"B2\", \"C3\", \"D4\"]\nweights = [12,   30,   8,    22]\n# heaviest weight is 30  ->  B2\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is **find-the-extreme**, with a twist: you don't just want the biggest weight, you want *which* parcel it belongs to. Track the position, not just the value.", "hints": ["Find-extreme pattern: assume the first parcel wins to start — `best = 0` — and remember the position, not just the number.", "Loop over positions so you can read both lists at once: `for i in range(len(weights)):` lets you compare `weights[i]` and recall `ids[i]`.", "When `weights[i] > weights[best]:`, update `best = i`. After the loop, the answer is `ids[best]`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Track the winning index", "code": "ids     = [\"A1\", \"B2\", \"C3\", \"D4\"]\nweights = [12, 30, 8, 22]\nbest = 0\nfor i in range(len(weights)):\n    if weights[i] > weights[best]:\n        best = i\nprint(ids[best])", "explanation": "Remember the *position* of the biggest so far; that one position indexes into both lists."}, {"label": "Pair them with zip", "code": "ids     = [\"A1\", \"B2\", \"C3\", \"D4\"]\nweights = [12, 30, 8, 22]\nbest_id, best_w = ids[0], weights[0]\nfor pid, w in zip(ids, weights):\n    if w > best_w:\n        best_id, best_w = pid, w\nprint(best_id)", "explanation": "`zip` walks both lists together so you handle one (id, weight) pair at a time — often cleaner than indexing."}]}, {"id": "tally-orders-by-city", "title": "Tally Orders by City", "difficulty": "hard", "description": "`cities` lists the destination of each order. Print a dictionary counting how many orders go to each city.\n\n```python\ncities = [\"Hanoi\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\", \"Danang\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\"]\n# expected output:\n{'Hanoi': 3, 'Hue': 2, 'Danang': 1}\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is the **group-and-count** (tally) shape — the loop version of a pivot table or pandas' `value_counts()`. Instead of one counter, you keep a *dictionary* of counters, one per category.", "hints": ["Tally pattern: start with an empty dict `counts = {}` before the loop — it grows a new counter the first time it meets each city.", "The tricky moment is the *first* time you see a city: there's no count to add 1 to yet. Handle it with `if city not in counts: counts[city] = 0` first.", "Once you know the key exists, `counts[city] += 1`. (Shortcut: `counts.get(city, 0) + 1` treats a never-seen city as 0.)"], "solutions": [{"label": "Dict of counters", "code": "cities = [\"Hanoi\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\", \"Danang\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\"]\ncounts = {}\nfor city in cities:\n    if city not in counts:\n        counts[city] = 0\n    counts[city] += 1\nprint(counts)", "explanation": "First time: create the counter at 0. Every time: add 1. This is the heart of grouping data."}, {"label": "get() shortcut", "code": "cities = [\"Hanoi\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\", \"Danang\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\"]\ncounts = {}\nfor city in cities:\n    counts[city] = counts.get(city, 0) + 1\nprint(counts)", "explanation": "`counts.get(city, 0)` returns the current count, or 0 if the city is new — collapsing the two cases into one line."}, {"label": "Counter (library)", "code": "from collections import Counter\ncities = [\"Hanoi\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\", \"Danang\", \"Hue\", \"Hanoi\"]\nprint(dict(Counter(cities)))", "explanation": "`Counter` does exactly this tally for you — but build the dict by hand first so you know what it's doing."}]}, {"id": "revenue-from-two-lists", "title": "Total Revenue", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Each product sold has a quantity and a unit price, in two parallel lists. Print the **total revenue** (quantity times price, summed over all products).\n\n```python\nquantities = [3, 1, 4, 2]\nprices     = [10, 25, 5, 50]\n# 3*10 + 1*25 + 4*5 + 2*50  =  30 + 25 + 20 + 100  ->  175\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nA **running total** again — but each step needs *two* values that belong together. `zip` lines the lists up so you get a matching pair each time around.", "hints": ["Accumulator again: `revenue = 0` before the loop, print after.", "Walk both lists in lockstep: `for qty, price in zip(quantities, prices):` hands you a matched pair each iteration.", "Inside the loop, add this product's line total: `revenue += qty * price`."], "solutions": [{"label": "zip and accumulate", "code": "quantities = [3, 1, 4, 2]\nprices     = [10, 25, 5, 50]\nrevenue = 0\nfor qty, price in zip(quantities, prices):\n    revenue += qty * price\nprint(revenue)", "explanation": "`zip` pairs each quantity with its price; multiply the pair and add it to the running total."}, {"label": "sum with zip", "code": "quantities = [3, 1, 4, 2]\nprices     = [10, 25, 5, 50]\nprint(sum(qty * price for qty, price in zip(quantities, prices)))", "explanation": "Same idea on one line: produce each line total, then `sum` them all."}]}, {"id": "running-inventory", "title": "Running Inventory", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Each day the warehouse receives some pallets. Print the **running inventory** — a list where each entry is the total received *so far*, up to and including that day.\n\n```python\nreceived = [5, 3, 0, 7, 2]\n# day-by-day totals:\n[5, 8, 8, 15, 17]\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is a **running total you record at every step** (a 'cumulative sum'). Keep one accumulator, but `append` its current value each day instead of only printing it at the end.", "hints": ["Two variables: a `total = 0` accumulator and an empty `running = []` to collect snapshots.", "Each day, first add, then record: `total += day`, then `running.append(total)`.", "Order matters — append *after* adding so that day's pallets are included. Print `running` at the end."], "solutions": [{"label": "Accumulate and snapshot", "code": "received = [5, 3, 0, 7, 2]\ntotal = 0\nrunning = []\nfor day in received:\n    total += day\n    running.append(total)\nprint(running)", "explanation": "One running total, captured into the list after each day's update."}]}, {"id": "sales-per-product", "title": "Sales per Product", "difficulty": "hard", "description": "Each sale is a small record with a product and a quantity. Total the quantity **per product** and print the result as a dictionary.\n\n```python\nsales = [\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 3},\n    {\"product\": \"tape\", \"qty\": 5},\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 2},\n    {\"product\": \"tape\", \"qty\": 1},\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 4},\n]\n# expected output:\n{'box': 9, 'tape': 6}\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is the **group-and-sum** shape — a tally, but you add the quantity instead of 1. A list of records (dicts) is exactly how a data table is stored, so this is the loop behind pandas' `groupby`.", "hints": ["Reach into each record by key: `sale[\"product\"]` and `sale[\"qty\"]`. Loop with `for sale in sales:`.", "Tally into `totals = {}`. The first time you meet a product, start it at 0: `if name not in totals: totals[name] = 0`.", "Then add this sale's quantity (not 1): `totals[name] += sale[\"qty\"]`. (Shortcut: `totals.get(name, 0) + sale[\"qty\"]`.)"], "solutions": [{"label": "Group and sum", "code": "sales = [\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 3},\n    {\"product\": \"tape\", \"qty\": 5},\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 2},\n    {\"product\": \"tape\", \"qty\": 1},\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 4},\n]\ntotals = {}\nfor sale in sales:\n    name = sale[\"product\"]\n    if name not in totals:\n        totals[name] = 0\n    totals[name] += sale[\"qty\"]\nprint(totals)", "explanation": "A tally that adds each record's quantity into the right product's bucket."}, {"label": "get() shortcut", "code": "sales = [\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 3},\n    {\"product\": \"tape\", \"qty\": 5},\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 2},\n    {\"product\": \"tape\", \"qty\": 1},\n    {\"product\": \"box\",  \"qty\": 4},\n]\ntotals = {}\nfor sale in sales:\n    name = sale[\"product\"]\n    totals[name] = totals.get(name, 0) + sale[\"qty\"]\nprint(totals)", "explanation": "`get(name, 0)` treats a never-seen product as 0, collapsing the two cases."}]}]}, {"id": "while-loops-and-limits", "title": "While Loops & Limits", "problems": [{"id": "load-the-truck", "title": "Load the Truck", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Parcels wait in a queue and are loaded in order. The truck holds **50 kg**. Load parcels one by one until the *next* one wouldn't fit, then stop. Print how many parcels you managed to load.\n\n```python\nparcels = [20, 15, 10, 8, 30]\n# 20 -> 35 -> 45; next is 8 -> would be 53, too heavy, stop  ->  3 loaded\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nYou don't know how many fit ahead of time — *that* is the signal to reach for `while` instead of `for`. Keep a running `load` and an index, and loop while there's both room and parcels left.", "hints": ["Track two things: `load = 0` (weight on board) and `i = 0` (which parcel you're looking at).", "The condition guards *before* you add: `while i < len(parcels) and load + parcels[i] <= 50:` — stop if you'd run off the list or overflow the truck.", "Inside the loop you must move forward yourself: `load += parcels[i]` then `i += 1`. Forgetting `i += 1` loops forever. The answer is `i`."], "solutions": [{"label": "while with a guard", "code": "parcels = [20, 15, 10, 8, 30]\nload = 0\ni = 0\nwhile i < len(parcels) and load + parcels[i] <= 50:\n    load += parcels[i]\n    i += 1\nprint(i)", "explanation": "The condition checks there's still a parcel *and* that it fits before loading. `i` ends up as the number loaded."}, {"label": "for with break", "code": "parcels = [20, 15, 10, 8, 30]\nload = 0\ncount = 0\nfor p in parcels:\n    if load + p > 50:\n        break\n    load += p\n    count += 1\nprint(count)", "explanation": "Same logic as a `for` loop that `break`s the moment the next parcel won't fit — no manual index needed."}]}, {"id": "burn-down-backlog", "title": "Burn Down the Backlog", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "A warehouse starts with `backlog = 27` orders. Your team clears `per_day = 5` orders each day. Print how many **days** it takes to clear the whole backlog (the last day counts even if it isn't a full day's worth).\n\n```python\nbacklog = 27\nper_day = 5\n# 27 -> 22 -> 17 -> 12 -> 7 -> 2 -> cleared  ->  6 days (the last clears just 2)\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is **drain-to-zero**: repeat *while there's still work left*, subtracting each round and counting the rounds. A number that goes down, plus a tally of steps.", "hints": ["You're counting rounds, so keep `days = 0`. The loop runs `while backlog > 0:`.", "Each pass does two updates: shrink the work and count the day — `backlog -= per_day` and `days += 1`.", "Don't worry that the last day subtracts more than is left (2 - 5 = -3); the condition `> 0` still stops correctly. Print `days` after the loop."], "solutions": [{"label": "Count the rounds", "code": "backlog = 27\nper_day = 5\ndays = 0\nwhile backlog > 0:\n    backlog -= per_day\n    days += 1\nprint(days)", "explanation": "Each loop is one day: reduce the backlog and tick the counter until nothing is left."}, {"label": "Math shortcut", "code": "import math\nbacklog = 27\nper_day = 5\nprint(math.ceil(backlog / per_day))", "explanation": "Rounding the division *up* gives the same answer — the loop just makes the partial last day obvious."}]}, {"id": "demand-doubling", "title": "When Demand Outgrows the Warehouse", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Daily demand starts at `demand = 100` units and **grows 50% each week** (multiply by 1.5). The warehouse ships at most `capacity = 1000` units a day. Print how many **weeks** until demand first exceeds capacity.\n\n```python\ndemand = 100, capacity = 1000\n# wk1 150, wk2 225, wk3 337, wk4 505, wk5 757, wk6 1135 (> 1000)  ->  6\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\n**Repeat-until-threshold**: you don't know the week count up front, so loop *while* you're still under the limit, growing the number and counting weeks. Use `int(...)` to keep whole units.", "hints": ["Count with `weeks = 0`, and loop `while demand <= capacity:` — keep going as long as you're still within capacity.", "Each week, grow then count: `demand = int(demand * 1.5)` and `weeks += 1`.", "The loop stops the first week `demand` passes `capacity`; that week is already counted, so just print `weeks`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Grow until over", "code": "demand = 100\ncapacity = 1000\nweeks = 0\nwhile demand <= capacity:\n    demand = int(demand * 1.5)\n    weeks += 1\nprint(weeks)", "explanation": "Multiply each week and count; the `while` naturally stops the moment demand passes capacity."}]}, {"id": "first-over-budget", "title": "First Order Over Budget", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "You process orders in order, adding up their cost as you go. The budget is **500**. Print the **position** (1-based) of the order at which your *cumulative* spend first goes over budget.\n\n```python\ncosts = [120, 90, 300, 60, 200]\n# running total: 120, 210, 510 -> crosses 500 at the 3rd order  ->  3\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is **search with early exit**: scan, keep a running total, and the instant it crosses the line, stop and report where you are. `break` is how you leave a loop early.", "hints": ["Running total again — `spent = 0` — but this time you'll stop mid-loop instead of finishing it.", "`enumerate(costs, start=1)` gives you both the position and the cost: `for position, cost in enumerate(costs, start=1):`.", "Add first, then check: `spent += cost`, then `if spent > 500: print(position); break`. The `break` leaves immediately, so you report the *first* crossing, not the last."], "solutions": [{"label": "Scan and break", "code": "costs = [120, 90, 300, 60, 200]\nspent = 0\nfor position, cost in enumerate(costs, start=1):\n    spent += cost\n    if spent > 500:\n        print(position)\n        break", "explanation": "`enumerate` numbers the orders; `break` stops the scan the moment the running total crosses 500."}]}, {"id": "count-the-digits", "title": "Count the Digits", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Print how many **digits** a positive whole number `n` has — without converting it to a string.\n\n```python\nn = 9072\n# 9, 0, 7, 2  ->  4 digits\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nChopping the last digit off a number is `n // 10`. Keep doing that, counting each chop, until nothing is left — a classic `while`.", "hints": ["`n // 10` removes the last digit (9072 becomes 907). Repeat until `n` reaches 0.", "Count the chops: `digits = 0`, loop `while n > 0:`, and `digits += 1` each pass.", "Inside the loop you must shrink `n`: `n = n // 10`. Forgetting it loops forever."], "solutions": [{"label": "Chop digits off", "code": "n = 9072\ndigits = 0\nwhile n > 0:\n    digits += 1\n    n = n // 10\nprint(digits)", "explanation": "Each pass drops one digit and counts it, until the number is gone."}]}, {"id": "sum-of-digits", "title": "Sum of Digits", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Add up the digits of a positive whole number `n`.\n\n```python\nn = 1234\n# 1 + 2 + 3 + 4  ->  10\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nTwo operators do the work: `n % 10` reads the **last** digit, and `n // 10` **removes** it. Loop until the number is gone, summing as you go.", "hints": ["`n % 10` gives the last digit (1234 % 10 is 4). `n // 10` drops it (1234 becomes 123).", "Running total: `total = 0`, loop `while n > 0:`, add the last digit each pass.", "Inside: `total += n % 10`, then `n = n // 10`. Read the digit *before* you chop it off."], "solutions": [{"label": "Peel and add", "code": "n = 1234\ntotal = 0\nwhile n > 0:\n    total += n % 10\n    n = n // 10\nprint(total)", "explanation": "Read the last digit, add it, remove it, and repeat until none remain."}]}, {"id": "reverse-a-number", "title": "Reverse a Number", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Print the digits of a positive whole number `n` in reverse order, as a number.\n\n```python\nn = 1234  ->  4321\nn = 1200  ->  21   (leading zeros simply disappear)\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nBuild the answer one digit at a time: each pass, peel the last digit off `n` and **tack it onto** the result by shifting the result left (multiply by 10) first.", "hints": ["Same digit tools: `n % 10` is the last digit, `n // 10` removes it.", "Grow the result by shifting it left then adding: `result = result * 10 + n % 10`.", "Do that `while n > 0:`, and don't forget `n = n // 10` to advance. Print `result`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Build it in reverse", "code": "n = 1234\nresult = 0\nwhile n > 0:\n    result = result * 10 + n % 10\n    n = n // 10\nprint(result)", "explanation": "Each digit peeled off the end is pushed onto the front of the result."}]}, {"id": "restock-until-target", "title": "Restock Until Target", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Stock starts at `stock = 12` units. Each delivery adds `per_delivery = 8` units. Print how many **deliveries** are needed to reach the target of **50** units.\n\n```python\nstock = 12, per_delivery = 8, target = 50\n# 12 -> 20 -> 28 -> 36 -> 44 -> 52  ->  5 deliveries\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThe mirror image of draining a backlog: keep adding *while you're still short of the target*, counting deliveries.", "hints": ["Count with `deliveries = 0`, and loop `while stock < 50:` — keep going while under target.", "Each pass: `stock += per_delivery` and `deliveries += 1`.", "The loop stops the first time stock reaches or passes 50; that delivery is already counted, so print `deliveries`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Add until target", "code": "stock = 12\nper_delivery = 8\ndeliveries = 0\nwhile stock < 50:\n    stock += per_delivery\n    deliveries += 1\nprint(deliveries)", "explanation": "Each loop is one delivery; keep adding until the target is met."}]}, {"id": "pay-off-the-loan", "title": "Pay Off the Loan", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "A `balance` of 1000 grows **1% interest each month**, then you pay `payment = 150`. Print how many **months** until the balance reaches 0 or below.\n\n```python\nbalance = 1000, interest = 1% per month, payment = 150\n# each month: balance = balance * 1.01 - 150\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\n**Repeat-until-cleared**: loop *while* you still owe money, applying interest then the payment each month, counting months. (The payment must beat the monthly interest, or the balance never falls.)", "hints": ["Loop `while balance > 0:`, counting `months += 1` each pass.", "Apply the two effects in order: interest `balance = balance * 1.01`, then payment `balance = balance - payment`. Combined: `balance = balance * 1.01 - payment`.", "Because 150 exceeds the monthly interest, the balance shrinks each month and the loop ends. Print `months`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Interest then payment", "code": "balance = 1000\npayment = 150\nmonths = 0\nwhile balance > 0:\n    balance = balance * 1.01 - payment\n    months += 1\nprint(months)", "explanation": "Each month adds interest then subtracts the payment, until the debt is cleared."}]}, {"id": "bouncing-ball", "title": "Bouncing Ball", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "A ball is dropped from `height = 100` cm. Each bounce reaches **half** the previous height. Print how many **bounces** until it rises to less than **1 cm**.\n\n```python\nheight = 100\n# 50, 25, 12.5, 6.25, 3.125, 1.5625, 0.78125  ->  7 bounces\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\n**Repeat-until-below-threshold**: halve the height each bounce, counting bounces, while it still reaches 1 cm or more.", "hints": ["Count `bounces = 0`, loop `while height >= 1:` — keep bouncing while it still rises to at least 1 cm.", "Each bounce halves it: `height = height / 2` and `bounces += 1`.", "Using `/` keeps the decimals (12.5, 6.25, ...). The loop ends once height drops below 1; print `bounces`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Halve until tiny", "code": "height = 100\nbounces = 0\nwhile height >= 1:\n    height = height / 2\n    bounces += 1\nprint(bounces)", "explanation": "Each pass halves the height and counts a bounce until it falls below 1 cm."}]}]}, {"id": "lists-and-strings", "title": "Lists & Strings", "problems": [{"id": "reverse-a-list", "title": "Reverse a List", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Given a list of numbers `nums`, print the list reversed.\n\n### Example\n```python\nnums = [1, 2, 3, 4]  ->  [4, 3, 2, 1]\n```", "hints": ["Slicing with a step of -1 reverses a sequence: `nums[::-1]`.", "There's also a `.reverse()` method that flips the list in place.", "And `reversed(nums)` gives you the items back-to-front (wrap it in `list(...)` to see them)."], "solutions": [{"label": "Slice trick", "code": "nums = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nprint(nums[::-1])", "explanation": "`[::-1]` means: take the whole list, stepping backwards one at a time."}, {"label": "In place", "code": "nums = [1, 2, 3, 4]\nnums.reverse()\nprint(nums)", "explanation": "`.reverse()` changes the original list rather than making a new one."}]}, {"id": "find-the-largest-number", "title": "Find the Largest Number", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Given a non-empty list `nums`, print the largest value **without using the built-in `max()`**.\n\n### Example\n```python\nnums = [4, 9, 2, 7]  ->  9\n```\n\nDoing it by hand first is the point — then compare with `max()`.", "hints": ["Start by assuming the first item is the biggest: `biggest = nums[0]`.", "Walk through the rest and update `biggest` whenever you find something larger.", "`if n > biggest: biggest = n` is the comparison you need inside the loop."], "solutions": [{"label": "Track the biggest", "code": "nums = [4, 9, 2, 7]\nbiggest = nums[0]\nfor n in nums:\n    if n > biggest:\n        biggest = n\nprint(biggest)", "explanation": "Hold onto the largest value seen so far and replace it whenever a bigger one shows up."}, {"label": "With max() (compare)", "code": "nums = [4, 9, 2, 7]\nprint(max(nums))", "explanation": "`max()` does exactly the same scan internally — handy once you understand what it's doing."}]}, {"id": "remove-duplicates", "title": "Remove Duplicates", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Given a list `items`, print a new list with duplicates removed, **keeping the original order** of first appearance.\n\n### Example\n```python\nitems = [3, 1, 3, 2, 1]  ->  [3, 1, 2]\n```", "hints": ["A `set` automatically drops duplicates — but it does **not** preserve order, so it's only half the answer.", "Keep a `seen` set and a `result` list; add each item to `result` only the first time you see it.", "`if item not in seen:` then append it and record it in `seen`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Order-preserving", "code": "items = [3, 1, 3, 2, 1]\nseen = set()\nresult = []\nfor item in items:\n    if item not in seen:\n        seen.add(item)\n        result.append(item)\nprint(result)", "explanation": "The `seen` set makes the 'have I met this before?' check fast, while `result` preserves order."}, {"label": "dict.fromkeys", "code": "items = [3, 1, 3, 2, 1]\nprint(list(dict.fromkeys(items)))", "explanation": "Dictionary keys are unique and (since Python 3.7) keep insertion order — a neat one-line trick."}]}, {"id": "sum-of-even-numbers", "title": "Sum of Even Numbers", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Given a list `nums`, print the sum of just the **even** numbers.\n\n```python\nnums = [4, 7, 10, 3, 6]\n# evens are 4, 10, 6  ->  20\n```", "hints": ["Filter while you total: keep `total = 0`, and add a number only when it's even.", "A number is even when `n % 2 == 0`.", "Inside the loop: `if n % 2 == 0: total += n`. Print `total` after."], "solutions": [{"label": "Add the evens", "code": "nums = [4, 7, 10, 3, 6]\ntotal = 0\nfor n in nums:\n    if n % 2 == 0:\n        total += n\nprint(total)", "explanation": "A running total that only accepts numbers passing the even test."}, {"label": "Sum a comprehension", "code": "nums = [4, 7, 10, 3, 6]\nprint(sum(n for n in nums if n % 2 == 0))", "explanation": "The `if` filters the values; `sum` totals the ones that get through."}]}, {"id": "count-the-words", "title": "Count the Words", "difficulty": "easy", "description": "Print how many **words** are in a sentence (words are separated by spaces).\n\n```python\nsentence = \"ship the order today\"\n# 4 words  ->  4\n```", "hints": ["`sentence.split()` breaks the text into a list of words at the spaces.", "The number of words is just the length of that list.", "`print(len(sentence.split()))`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Split and count", "code": "sentence = \"ship the order today\"\nwords = sentence.split()\nprint(len(words))", "explanation": "Splitting on spaces makes a list of words; its length is the count."}]}, {"id": "capitalize-every-name", "title": "Capitalize Every Name", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Given a list of lowercase city names, print a new list with each name **capitalized** (first letter uppercase).\n\n```python\ncities = [\"hanoi\", \"hue\", \"danang\"]\n# expected output:\n['Hanoi', 'Hue', 'Danang']\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nThis is the **transform** shape: one name in, one capitalized name out, same length list. Build the new list with `append`.", "hints": ["Transform pattern: empty `result = []`, then `append` one cleaned name per city.", "`name.capitalize()` uppercases the first letter and lowercases the rest.", "Every city produces exactly one output, so there's no `if` around the `append`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Capitalize each", "code": "cities = [\"hanoi\", \"hue\", \"danang\"]\nresult = []\nfor name in cities:\n    result.append(name.capitalize())\nprint(result)", "explanation": "One transformed name appended per input — the result matches the input length."}, {"label": "Comprehension", "code": "cities = [\"hanoi\", \"hue\", \"danang\"]\nprint([name.capitalize() for name in cities])", "explanation": "The transform loop written on a single line."}]}, {"id": "second-largest", "title": "Second Largest", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Given a list of numbers (no ties at the top), print the **second largest** value.\n\n```python\nnums = [4, 9, 2, 7, 8]\n# largest is 9, second largest  ->  8\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nOne reliable route: sort the numbers and read the second from the end. The hand-rolled route tracks the top two as you scan.", "hints": ["`sorted(nums)` returns the numbers in ascending order without changing the original.", "In a sorted-ascending list, the largest is last (`[-1]`) and the second largest is `[-2]`.", "Hand-rolled alternative: track `first` and `second`; when a number beats `first`, the old `first` slides down to `second`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Sort and pick", "code": "nums = [4, 9, 2, 7, 8]\nprint(sorted(nums)[-2])", "explanation": "Sorted ascending, the second-from-last element is the second largest."}, {"label": "Track top two", "code": "nums = [4, 9, 2, 7, 8]\nfirst = second = float(\"-inf\")\nfor n in nums:\n    if n > first:\n        second = first\n        first = n\n    elif n > second:\n        second = n\nprint(second)", "explanation": "Keep the best and runner-up as you scan; a new winner demotes the old one."}]}, {"id": "most-common-word", "title": "Most Common Word", "difficulty": "hard", "description": "Given a list of words, print the one that appears **most often**.\n\n```python\nwords = [\"box\", \"tape\", \"box\", \"bag\", \"box\", \"tape\"]\n# 'box' appears 3 times  ->  box\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nTwo patterns back to back: first **tally** each word into a dict of counts, then **find the extreme** — the key with the highest count. This is the loop behind 'most frequent value'.", "hints": ["Step 1 — tally: build `counts = {}` with `counts[word] = counts.get(word, 0) + 1` for each word.", "Step 2 — find the extreme: scan the dict for the key with the biggest value, tracking `best` as you go.", "Loop the pairs with `for word, c in counts.items():` and keep the word whose count is highest."], "solutions": [{"label": "Tally then find max", "code": "words = [\"box\", \"tape\", \"box\", \"bag\", \"box\", \"tape\"]\ncounts = {}\nfor word in words:\n    counts[word] = counts.get(word, 0) + 1\nbest = None\nbest_count = 0\nfor word, c in counts.items():\n    if c > best_count:\n        best = word\n        best_count = c\nprint(best)", "explanation": "Count every word, then scan the counts for the highest — a tally feeding a find-the-extreme."}, {"label": "With max()", "code": "words = [\"box\", \"tape\", \"box\", \"bag\", \"box\", \"tape\"]\ncounts = {}\nfor word in words:\n    counts[word] = counts.get(word, 0) + 1\nprint(max(counts, key=counts.get))", "explanation": "`max(..., key=counts.get)` picks the word whose count is largest."}]}, {"id": "average-of-each-row", "title": "Average of Each Row", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "A small table is stored as a list of rows, each row a list of numbers. Print a list with the **average of each row**.\n\n```python\ntable = [[10, 20, 30], [4, 8], [5, 5, 5, 5]]\n# row averages: 20.0, 6.0, 5.0\n[20.0, 6.0, 5.0]\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nA loop **inside** a loop — but the inner work is one you know: sum a row and divide by its length. Each outer step turns one row into one average.", "hints": ["Transform over rows: empty `averages = []`, append one number per row.", "For a single row you already know the move: `sum(row) / len(row)`.", "`for row in table: averages.append(sum(row) / len(row))`, then print the list."], "solutions": [{"label": "Average each row", "code": "table = [[10, 20, 30], [4, 8], [5, 5, 5, 5]]\naverages = []\nfor row in table:\n    averages.append(sum(row) / len(row))\nprint(averages)", "explanation": "Each row collapses to its own average, collected into one list."}]}, {"id": "clean-the-data", "title": "Clean the Data", "difficulty": "medium", "description": "Raw data often has blanks. Given a list that mixes real values with empty strings and `None`, print a clean list with the junk removed, order preserved.\n\n```python\nrows = [\"hanoi\", \"\", \"hue\", None, \"danang\", \"\"]\n# expected output:\n['hanoi', 'hue', 'danang']\n```\n\n### Plan before you type\nA **filter**: keep only the values that are real. In Python both empty strings and `None` are 'falsy', so a single truth test screens them both out.", "hints": ["Filter pattern: empty `clean = []`, append only the good values.", "Both `\"\"` and `None` count as falsy — so `if value:` is True only for real, non-empty values.", "`for value in rows: if value: clean.append(value)`. Print `clean`."], "solutions": [{"label": "Keep the truthy ones", "code": "rows = [\"hanoi\", \"\", \"hue\", None, \"danang\", \"\"]\nclean = []\nfor value in rows:\n    if value:\n        clean.append(value)\nprint(clean)", "explanation": "`if value:` is False for `\"\"` and `None`, so only real entries are kept."}, {"label": "Comprehension", "code": "rows = [\"hanoi\", \"\", \"hue\", None, \"danang\", \"\"]\nprint([v for v in rows if v])", "explanation": "The same falsy filter, written as a one-line comprehension."}]}]}]};
